The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Metro | Career fair on campus 
                                                                                                               Career fair on campus 
  - Xaviers calls city students          A STAFF REPORTER                          Students check out the stalls of Gurukul Edunar 09 on Friday. Picture by Sanjoy Chattopadhyaya                                        
	St Xaviers College is hosting an education fair this weekend to help guide city students on further studies and career choices. Organised by the St Xaviers College (Calcutta) Alumni Association and the Lions Club of Calcutta, Park Street, in association with The Telegraph, Gurukul Edunar 09 is being held on the colleges Park Street campus between June 12 and 15.        
	It will be open to all city students from 11am to 8pm. At this fair students will get a variety of information that will help them make an informed decision about their careers, said college principal Father Felix Raj.        
	The fair was inaugurated on Friday by the principal. I came to the college to check my admission results and found out about the fair. I dropped in to see what options I have after graduation, said Reema Das, who has just cleared the ISC exams.        
	The four-day educational extravaganza has around 30 local, national and international participating institutes covering a wide range of options from the traditional engineering and MBA to event management, interior designing and fashion designing.        
	The local institutes present include the JIS group, Bengal Institute of Business Studies and the Pailan Group. National institutes like NDIMS, New Delhi, JP Institute of Engineering and Technology, Meerut, and Leviosa Business School, Bangalore, are also participating in the fair.        
	Australasian Lawrence Aged Care College and EMDI, an event management and media and communications institute with branches in Dubai, Mumbai, Delhi, Bangalore and Pune, are adding the global touch.        
	The reason behind organising this event was to provide students with various career options under one roof. The funds generated through the fair will be used for social service, said association secretary Firdausal Hassan.         
	The fair will host seminars on career options  from the Indian taxation system, radio jockeying, disk jockeying, interior designing to community welfare in Australia  on June 13 and 14.                                                                                                                                                                           
